"1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"1440–":"1440–Afdød","1440–Male":"1440–Afdød","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Afdød","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"nl":{"1440–":"1440–Overleden","1440–Male":"1440–Overleden","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Overleden","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"en":{"1440–":"1440–Deceased","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Deceased","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pepys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Old French personal name  <i>Pepis</i>. It is a nominative form of  <i>Pepon</i>, a French version of Continental Germanic  <i>Pipo</i>, and probably related to Old French  <i>Pepin</i>.  See  Peppin  . The personal name was extremely rare in medieval England. (ii) relationship name; alternatively it may mean; ‘Philip’s (son/relative/servant)’, from the genitive singular of Middle English * <i>Pip</i>, * <i>Pep</i>, side-forms perhaps of  <i>Phip</i>,  <i>Phep</i>, pet forms of Middle English  <i>Philip</i>,  <i>Phelip</i>.  Compare  Peppin  ,   Phippen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Phippen","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): shortened form of the Anglo-Norman surname <i>Fitzpain</i> ‘son of <i>Pain</i>’ (see   Payne  ).","English: variant of <b>Phipp</b> with the West Midlands Middle English genitive singular <i>-en</i> instead of the more usual <i>-s</i>, see   Phipps  . Alternatively, perhaps from the unattested Middle English personal names <i>Phippon</i> or <i>Phippin</i>, which could be Old French pet forms of   Philip  , though they are not on record.","Irish: perhaps an altered form of   Thigpen   by association or confusion with the name in (1). The 17th-century <i>Thigpen</i> and <i>Phippen</i> families in NC were apparently related."]},{"name":"Peppin","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Pepin  ."]},{"name":"Pipes","meanings":["English: variant of   Pipe  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705201,"age":109,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":118,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Pepys was born in 1440, in England as the son of Thomas Pepys. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1440–":"1440–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Surnud","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fi":{"1440–":"1440–Kuollut","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fr":{"1440–":"1440–Décédé","1440–Male":"1440–Décédé","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Décédé","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Pepys est né en 1440, à Angleterre, fils de Thomas Pepys. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1440–":"1440–Verstorben","1440–Male":"1440–Verstorben","1464–1519":"1464–1519","1389–Male":"1389–Verstorben","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1389":"1